		Interactive ListProcessor(tm) Protocol (ILPP) IIb
		-------------------------------------------------

Date: May 15 1995
Author: Anastasios Kotsikonas

PURPOSE
-------

This document attempts to explain the protocol used by an Interactive
ListProcessor(tm), version 2b. Comments are most welcome.

OVERVIEW
--------

ListProcessor(tm) is an automated mailing list and archive system, supported
only on UNIX platforms. By default, all communication is performed over
electronic mail. Versions 6.0 and above are also capable of accepting
live TCP/IP connections over the Internet, for processing of user requests.
The privileged port #372 has been assigned by the IANA for this purpose.
This document attempts to clarify the protocol between server and client,
and although a client is provided to users by the author, better ones
are possible.

Version 2 of this protocol maintains 100% compatibility with version 1, and
expands it for development purposes of various event driven graphical clients
(like X). Version 2 introduces a new reply code, 107, which substitutes
the "request> " prompt as the input ready signal.

Version 2a redefines an argument to the connection string; the timeout 
integer now signifies an idle timeout, as opposed to connection duration.

Version 2b corrects 2a's claim that the server sends character 0x3 as
out-of-band data for confirmation on a abort operation; the correct hex
code actually send is 0x23 ('#').

SERVER/CLIENT HANDSHAKE
-----------------------

Upon connection establishment a handshake operation takes place: the
server reports to the client the following parameters, all numbers, in
a single line terminated by a newline character (\n):

magic-cookie idle-timeout version primary-prompt-length continuation-prompt-length

Where 'magic-cookie' is a 3-digit number common to both sides so that the
client knows that it has connected to the right server. This number may
be anything under 400 (currently set at 105, see below). If the 'magic-cookie'
is over 400 (inclusive) no connection could be established. 'idle-timeout' is
reported in seconds, and represents the idle time after which the server may
arbitrarily break the connection. The server's version is provided for future
use. The system uses a primary prompt and a secondary one when a request is
either to be continued on the next line, or its arguments are not known.

SERVER/CLIENT COMMUNICATION
---------------------------

Each server/client transaction is based on server reply codes. For each
client request (i.e. each string terminated by a newline character) a
reply is generated by the server (except during login where more replies are
generated -- see below, and in the case where the server sends status reports
usually on delays); this reply may be followed by any number of lines of text.

Server replies have of the following format:

<Control string>\n
[Optional ListProcessor(tm) text ...
.
.
.
or file\n]

A control string always precedes the actual message/file sent by ListProcessor(tm).
This string spans one line and is terminated by a newline character (\n).
The control string consists of a 3-digit reply code, followed by a blank,
followed by the number of bytes of the actual message/file (>=0), followed
by a blank, optionally followed by a file name (if ListProcessor(tm) is to send a
file), and terminated by a newline character:

xyz #of-bytes [filename]\n

