800 System error		  (server/gateway aborted/various other errors)
860 Permission denied		   (cannot write/append to file on client side)
870 Server busy						 (too many connections)
880 Connection timed out				      (timeout expired)
890 Connection aborted					  (for various reasons)
900 Connection closed					   (normal termination)

SPECIAL CLIENT REQUESTS
-----------------------

0x3 - abort current operation; when the client wishes to abort the operation
      in progress, it sends character 0x3 to the server as out-of-band data,
      the server aborts what it's doing, sends character 0x23 ('#') for
      confirmation as out-of-band data, followed by the number of bytes
      transferred up to that point in an 8-byte message (the number is padded
      with leading zeroes, e.g. 00004356) as in-band data, and guarantees to
      send the prompt sequence next. Since the server may have finished
      writing the data when the client requests the abort operation, the
      client is advised to periodically send code 0x3 over the regular channel
      (in-band data) while waiting for the acknowledgement; this will awaken
      the server.

      It is the client's responsibility to look for the OOB mark discarding
      data as necessary, read the 8-byte message, get the prompt and continue.

"__abort__" - shutdown the connection immediately.

SERVER/SERVER COMMUNICATION
---------------------------

A user request may refer to a list that is served by a remote server known
to this server; since list names may not be unique across all servers, the user
may specify a full electronic mail address for that list to distinguish it
from the others. It is the local server's responsibility to chain-connect to
all remote server(s), get the reply/replies and forward it/them back to the
user. This chain-connection is currently limited to 5 hops, but is system-
configurable. Each participating ListProcessor(tm) installation keeps a database
of all known servers, their electronic mail addresses, their DNS or IP
addresses, and the ports they are listening to. If chain-connection cannot be
established, the user will have to resort to electronic mail; he may send
his request to this server which will in turn forward it to the proper one(s).

The protocol used during a client-to-server connection is identical to the
one described above.

CONNECTION ESTABLISHMENT
------------------------

Upon a successful handshake, the server initiates the login process,
where the user may identify himself by providing an email address as
subscribed to one of the lists (if any). The control string in this case is:

100 #of-bytes-of-greeting+email-prompt

Depending on the user reply, the server either asks for a password (the
user provides the password used in the list for which the email address
refers to), if the user did indeed specify an email address and then
proceeds to the main prompt, or reports OK and proceeds to the main prompt, if
no email address was specified.

In the former case, the first control string is:

103 #of-bytes-of-password-prompt

and the latter:

100 #of-bytes-of-help+prompt

In the latter case, the first control string reads:

100 0

and the second:

100 #of-bytes-of-help+prompt

After the handshake, the server may deny access by providing a "Server Busy",
"Connection Aborted", "Peer Unavailable", "Connection Timed Out" or "System
Error" reply:

400/800/870/880/890 #of-bytes-of-text

and close the connection. It reports "Peer Unavailable" (400) if it detects a
loop in the chain of live ListProcessor(tm) connections, or if a gateway could
not connect to the actual server.

REQUEST PROCESSING
------------------

Most requests/replies require a single server reply (whether or not the
request is valid). However, the server may send status reports on anticipated
delays when it is busy processing other requests; in this case, the client
is required to echo the message and keep polling for the actual reply to the
user's request. Since requests may be continued on multiple lines, the server
may issue continuation commands in the control string (102) and use the
secondary prompt. For example:

request> HELP &
102 2
> SET
100 1042
...
request>

The number of bytes following the reply code includes the primary prompt's
length, and the actual reply contains the prompt string at the end in all cases.

When the reply is to be redirected to a file however (as is the case during
a "get" request, or when explicitly redirecting the output), the server
requests from the client to verify that the output file has write permissions
(by providing the file name) and expects from the client "Permission Denied"
(860) or a go ahead:

154 0 filename

For example:

request> HELP SET > OUT
154 0 out

At this point, the client may send a 100 reply code and the server counter
replies with:

reply-code #of-bytes-of-file/text+prompt filename

This reply code must tell the client that the transfer is destined for
a file and must identify the type of transfer (ascii or binary).
Since the prompt is part of the reply, the client must isolate it from the
stream. If the client reports "Permission Denied" the server simply counter
replies with:

100 #length-of-prompt

Certain requests (like put) take an indefinite number of lines of text
as argument. For these requests, the server first replies with:

101 #of-bytes-of-explanatory-text

and expects input to finish with a single period ('.') in a line by itself.
For every such input line except the-end-of-input ('.') the server either
reports:

100 0

or in the case this line is continued on another line:

102 #length-of-secondary-prompt

At any point throughout the session, the server may abort, close or time
out the connection.

