VERSION 2 ENHANCEMENTS
----------------------

Version 2 introduces the 107 reply code, which replaces the "request> "
prompt as the input ready signal. Wherever this prompt was sent before, 
the byte account no longer accounts for the prompt length (because there
is no prompt!) and the server sends this new reply code to signal it is
ready for input. In other words, the server now sends two replies for each
request:

reply-code byte-count \n
contents
107 0 \n

The byte count after 107 is always zero. This behavior was introduced to
help event driven clients like xilp better synchronize with the server.
To turn on this behavior, all the client has to do is precede the email
address with the 8-character special string "__eilp__", even when there is no
email address specified.

In addition and if in __eilp__ mode, upon a "put" request the version 1 server
used to send 100 0 for each line typed and before the final ".\n", but version
2 does not send anything.

Finally, when the server receives an abort signal as explained above, it
will send 0x23 ('#') as out-band-data, then the message, and finally 107 0.
